        = partial "shared/braga_photo", locals: { photo: "/images/braga/arco.png", frame: "orange" }
        .u-smallPushBottom
        p.Text Take a stroll in the streets of the historic center, don’t forget to walk through the “Arco da Porta Nova”. This National Monument was once one the main entrances to medieval city and is where the keys to the city are presented to dignitaries and celebrities.

    .u-largePushRight.u-largePushBottom

    .Cage.bragaLargeAtMost
      .Flex.column
        = partial "shared/braga_photo", locals: { photo: "/images/braga/jesus.png", frame: "pink" }
        .u-smallPushBottom
        p.Text Take the 19th century hydraulic elevator which is one the oldest of its kind still functioning in the world to enjoy the peaceful ambience and outstanding views of “Santuário do Bom Jesus”. While there you should walk down the iconic 581-step Baroque stairway.

    .u-largePushRight.u-largePushBottom

    .Cage.bragaSmallAtMost
      .Flex.column
        = partial "shared/braga_photo", locals: { photo: "/images/braga/sameiro.png", frame: "pink" }
        .u-smallPushBottom
        p.Text AXA Stadium was carved out of a quarry on a mountain that overlooks the city. It has won multiple awards in the fields of architecture and civil engineering. While you are there, go to a match to support the home team, Sporting Club de Braga.

  .u-largePushBottom

